n of Thought and Reality -- t17. Exploring the Real Known World: A Metaphysical Beginning -- tThe Autograph, 1951-1953 -- t18. Finally Beginning in the Middle: Common Sense, Consciousness, and Self-Affirmation -- t19. Insights into Emergent Probability -- t20. Insights into the Dialectical Development of Common Sense -- t21. Insights into the Irreducibility of Things -- t22. Insights into Philosophical Method, Polymorphism, and Isomorphism -- t23. Process Metaphysics: Finality, Development, the Human Image -- t24. On Mythic and Philosophical Consciousness: Truth and Its Expression and Interpretation -- t25. The Cognitional and the Ethical -- t26. Questions and Insights in Religion -- t27. Introduction, Epilogue, Prefaces, Publication -- tEpilogue: Recollecting the Human Mystery -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tBernard Lonergan Index -- tGeneral Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aInsight is widely regarded as Bernard Lonergan?s masterwork. Worked out over a period of twenty-eight years, its aim was to present a theory of human knowing that underpinned the wide range of disciplines it addressed and their distinctive insights. In Lonergan?s Quest, William A. Mathews details the genesis, researching, composition, and question structure of Insight.The path toInsight began for Lonergan in the 1920s with his studies in philosophy at Heythrop College. Questioning many of the accepted truths of those studies, Lonergan's interests moved to economics while teaching in Depression-era Montreal, and later to theology and the philosophy of history while studying in Rome. The writing of Insight began in earnest in 1949 and soon evolved into Lonergan?s masterpiece, encompassing his many divergent, but philosophically coherent, streams of thought.An intellectual biography, Lonergan?s Quest locates Insight centrally within the broader philosophical tradition, presenting a new solution to the problem of the mind-world relation as posed by Immanuel Kant, as well as addressing the nature of consciousness. The book demonstrates that the desire of the human mind is also a narrative in time through which the intellectual identity of the author is forged and their relation with the text established.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aKnowledge, Theory of. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Epistemology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066769108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/9781442676794423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442676794.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066769-1  UTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG